Vaccination Impact: A Global Health & Economic Perspective

Author

Sanket Salke (DCU ID: 12977)

Introduction

This report explores global vaccination coverage[^1] This report explores the critical role of vaccination in enhancing public health. Our analysis shows that between 2000 and 2023, global vaccination coverage increased by 20%, while average life expectancy rose by 10 years. Regional data reveals that countries with strong economic and healthcare support achieve vaccination rates above 90%, compared to around 70% in less resourcedÂ nations.

STEADY INCREASE IN VACCINATION COVERAGE OVER THE YEARS, PARALLELED BY A RISE IN LIFE EXPECTANCY

Pandemic Impact (2020â2021) During 2020 and 2021, both vaccination coverage and life expectancy experienced a noticeable dip, coverage fell from roughly 85% down to 82%, while life expectancy dipped by 0.5 years. This reversal aligns with the global COVID-19 crisis, which strained healthcare systems, disrupted routine immunization campaigns, and diverted resources toward emergency response. It highlights the vulnerability of preventive health services during major outbreaks and underscores the need for resilient delivery systems that can maintain essential vaccinations even under pandemic pressures.

ð Conclusion

Over the past four decades, first-dose rubella vaccination coverage has climbed steadily from roughly 65% in 1980 to 85% by 2023, paralleled by life expectancy gains of eight years overall. Our time-series chart highlights a pandemic-driven 5-point dip in 2020â21, underscoring the fragility of routine immunization systems in the face of global disruption. The interactive world map reveals stark regional disparities: while Europe and North America maintain coverage above 90%, parts of Africa and Oceania still struggle below 70%. Zooming in with the GDP-coverage scatter, we see a clear positive correlation (râ0.6) between economic prosperity and immunization ratesâwealthier nations can more reliably procure, distribute, and administer vaccines. Finally, our multi-axis bar chart shows that years with stronger average vaccination growth also coincide with higher hospital bed availability and lower crude birth rates, suggesting that robust healthcare infrastructure and demographic transitions amplify the long-term benefits of immunization. Together, these analyses paint a cohesive narrative: sustained investment in vaccination programs, backed by solid healthcare resources and economic stability, delivers the greatest public-health dividendsâimproving survival, extending lifespans, and strengthening societal resilience.

ð¯ Recommendations

  1. Ensure Immunization Continuity During Crises
    Establish emergency contingency plans and mobile outreach teams to maintain routine vaccination servicesâand quickly recover coverageâduring pandemics, natural disasters, or other system shocks.

  2. Invest in Healthcare Infrastructure
    Expand hospital bed capacity, cold-chain networks, and trained personnel, particularly in underserved regions, to support both ongoing immunization campaigns and broader public-health delivery.

  3. Target Low-Coverage Regions with Tailored Programs
    Deploy community-driven outreach, subsidized vaccine financing, and culturally adapted communication in parts of Africa, Oceania, and other hotspots to close the persistent coverage gaps.

  4. Tie Economic Support to Immunization Goals
    Integrate vaccination financing into national health budgets and development plansâleveraging public-private partnerships and international fundingâto bolster supply, distribution, and equitable access.
